le|7053188}}\n\n{{Grey's Anatomy}}\n{{ABCNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n{{Portal bar|Television|United States}}\n\n[[Category:2018 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:American action television series]]\n[[Category:American television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series about firefighting]]\n[[Category:Television series by ABC Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Shondaland]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in California]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Seattle Fire Department]]\n", "name_user": "Emaponche", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast and characters", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Station_19"}
{"title_page": "Pension regulation", "text_new": "'''Pension regulation''' is a [[legal term]] encompassing, the set of laws, rules and authoritative standards governing the [[pension]] industry, and the procedures needed to enforce them. \n\nPension regulation varies widely from one [[jurisdiction]] to another - notably due to the persistence of discrepancies in the degree of [[autonomy]] and breadth of authority and [[discretionary power]] that national and regional pension regulators have at their disposal to enforce efficiently existing laws and regulations, in relation with local judicial practices and varying [[Jurisprudence|jurisprudential]] trends.<ref>{{in lang|en}} {{Citation |url= http://www.blakes.com/english/view_disc.asp?ID=268|accessdate=2005-09-01 |title= Blake, Cassels & Graydon Business Bulletin, 'Pension Regulation and Court Trends in British Columbia'}}</ref>\n\nPension regulation seeks to provide the various norms and standards needed to, foster market efficiency, consistency, transparency and accountability across the pension industry: it is a key driver of pension funds's risk management.\n\nIn Europe, in the wake of the 2008-2009 financial crisis, some pension experts such as Anton van Nunen have argued that excessive or misplaced regulatory activism can sometimes have negative [[unintended consequences]],<ref>{{in lang|en}} {{Citation |url=http://www.globalpensions.com/global-pensions/news/1932709/van-nunen-dutch-regulations-killing-pensions |accessdate=2011-03-20 |title=see Rachel Pichardo-Allison, \"Van Nunen: Dutch regulations \"killing\" pensions\",  15 Dec 2010}}</ref> notably when it comes to the strict enforcement of asset liability matching in times high market volatility and the systematic use of bonds-based risk metrics across all asset classes.\n\n== Kinds of pensions ==\n\n=== Voluntary or mandatory ===\n\n* Pension is voluntary, when employers are not required to offer a pension, and in case they do it, they have the right to decide about the volume and choose a type of pension.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Forman, Mackenzie|first=|date=November 21, 2013|title=The Cost of 'Choice' in a Voluntary Pension System|url=|journal=New York University Review of Employee Benefits and Executive Compensation|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n* Mandatory pension system obliges all citizens to make pension savings.\n\n=== Universal or Means tested ===\n\n* In case of universal pension every citizen gets a pension starting with a certain age.\n* Means-tested social pensions are those where eligibility is based on a test of the income of an individual.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kumru, Piggott|first=|date=February 13, 2010|title=Should Public Retirement Pensions Be Means-tested?|url=|journal=DEGIT Conference Papers|volume=|pages=|via=Google scholar}}</ref>\n\n=== PAYG or funded ===\n\n* PAYG (pay-as-you-go) is when current contributions paid for current pensions.\n* Funded system means that each individual's contributions pay directly for their pension benefits.<ref>{{Cite report |last=Palacios |first=Rober |last2=Whitehouse |first2=Edward |date=January 1998 |title=The Role of Choice in the Transition to a Funded Pension System |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/793071468128677426/The-role-of-choice-in-the-transition-to-a-funded-pension-system |publisher=The World Bank |series=Social Protection Discussion Paper Series No. 9812 |page=1}}</ref>\n\n=== Defined benefit (DB) or defined contribution (DC) ===\nThis characteristic defines a party bearing a risk. \n\n* Defined benefit: a person is provided with specified payments after retirement. Costs and risks relates to the provider.\n* Defined contribution:  employees and employers are allowed to contribute and invest funds over time to save for retirement. In this case payments depend on the financial system performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/032415/how-does-defined-benefit-pension-plan-differ-defined-contribution-plan.asp|title=Defined-Benefit Pension Plan vs. Defined-Contribution Plan: An Overview|last=|first=|date=March 23, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Law}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pension regulation}}\n[[Category:Business law]]\n[[Category:Pensions]]\n[[Category:Economics of regulation]]\n[[Category:Actuarial science]]\n[[Category:Legal research]]\n\n\n{{law-stub}}\n{{economics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Pension regulation''' is a [[legal term]] encompassing, the set of laws, rules and authoritative standards governing the [[pension]] industry, and the procedures needed to enforce them. \n\nPension regulation varies widely from one [[jurisdiction]] to another - notably due to the persistence of discrepancies in the degree of [[autonomy]] and breadth of authority and [[discretionary power]] that national and regional pension regulators have at their disposal to enforce efficiently existing laws and regulations, in relation with local judicial practices and varying [[Jurisprudence|jurisprudential]] trends.<ref>{{in lang|en}} {{Citation |url= http://www.blakes.com/english/view_disc.asp?ID=268|accessdate=2005-09-01 |title= Blake, Cassels & Graydon Business Bulletin, 'Pension Regulation and Court Trends in British Columbia'}}</ref>\n\nPension regulation seeks to provide the various norms and standards needed to, foster market efficiency, consistency, transparency and accountability across the pension industry: it is a key driver of pension funds's risk management.\n\nIn Europe, in the wake of the 2008-2009 financial crisis, some pension experts such as Anton van Nunen have argued that excessive or misplaced regulatory activism can sometimes have negative [[unintended consequences]],<ref>{{in lang|en}} {{Citation |url=http://www.globalpensions.com/global-pensions/news/1932709/van-nunen-dutch-regulations-killing-pensions |accessdate=2011-03-20 |title=see Rachel Pichardo-Allison, \"Van Nunen: Dutch regulations \"killing\" pensions\",  15 Dec 2010}}</ref> notably when it comes to the strict enforcement of asset liability matching in times high market volatility and the systematic use of bonds-based risk metrics across all asset classes.\n\n== Kinds of pensions ==\n\n=== Voluntary or mandatory ===\n\n* Pension is voluntary, when employers are not required to offer a pension, and in case they do it, they have the right to decide about the volume and choose a type of pension.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Forman, Mackenzie|first=|date=November 21, 2013|title=The Cost of 'Choice' in a Voluntary Pension System|url=|journal=New York University Review of Employee Benefits and Executive Compensation|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n* Mandatory pension system obliges all citizens to make pension savings.\n\n=== Universal or Means tested ===\n\n* In case of universal pension every citizen gets a pension starting with a certain age.\n* Means-tested social pensions are those where eligibility is based on a test of the income of an individual.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kumru, Piggott|first=|date=February 13, 2010|title=Should Public Retirement Pensions Be Means-tested?|url=|journal=DEGIT Conference Papers|volume=|pages=|via=Google scholar}}</ref>\n\n=== PAYG or funded ===\n\n* PAYG (pay-as-you-go) is when current contributions paid for current pensions.\n* Funded system means that each individual's contributions pay directly for their pension benefits.<ref>{{Cite report |last=Palacios |first=Rober |last2=Whitehouse |first2=Edward |date=January 1998 |title=The Role of Choice in the Transition to a Funded Pension System |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/793071468128677426/The-role-of-choice-in-the-transition-to-a-funded-pension-system |publisher=The World Bank |series=Social Protection Discussion Paper Series No. 9812 |page=1}}</ref>\n\n=== Defined benefit (DB) or defined contribution (DC) ===\nThis charakteristic defines a party bearing a risk. \n\n* Defined benefit: a person is provided with specified payments after retirement. Costs and risks relates to the provider.\n* Defined contribution:  employees and employers are allowed to contribute and invest funds over time to save for retirement. In this case payments depend on the financial system performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/032415/how-does-defined-benefit-pension-plan-differ-defined-contribution-plan.asp|title=Defined-Benefit Pension Plan vs. Defined-Contribution Plan: An Overview|last=|first=|date=March 23, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Law}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pension regulation}}\n[[Category:Business law]]\n[[Category:Pensions]]\n[[Category:Economics of regulation]]\n[[Category:Actuarial science]]\n[[Category:Legal research]]\n\n\n{{law-stub}}\n{{economics-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lee Vilenski", "label": "safe", "comment": "charakteristic->characteristic -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pension_regulation"}
{"title_page": "Peru", "text_new": "{{about|the country in South America}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|Country in South America}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Coord|10|S|76|W|display=title}}\n{{Infobox country\n| conventional_long_name                = Republic of Peru\n| native_name                = {{nobold|{{native name|es|Rep\u00fablica del Per\u00fa}}}}\n| common_name                = Peru\n| name                = {{collapsible list\n |titlestyle = background:transparent;line-height:normal;text-align:center;font-size:84%;\n |title      = {{resize|1.0 em|Co-official names}}{{efn|name=a|In Peru, [[Languages of Peru|other languages]] have been officially recognised as legitimate [[Indigenous language|autochthonous languages]]. In each of these,\n Peru's official name ({{lang-es|Rep\u00fablica del Per\u00fa|links=no}}, pronounced: {{IPA-es|re\u02c8pu\u03b2lika \u00f0el pe\u02c8\u027eu|}}) is as follows:\n* {{lang-qu|Piruw Republika}}<!-- , {{IPA-xx|xx|IPA}} -->\n* {{lang-ay|Piruw Suyu}}<!-- , {{IPA-xx|xx|IPA}} -->}}\n|{{Infobox\n |subbox=yes\n |bodystyle=font-size:80%;font-weight:normal;\n |rowclass1 = mergedrow\n |label1=[[Quechua language|Quechua]]:\n |data1={{lang|qu|Piruw Republika}}\n |rowclass2 = mergedrow\n |label2=[[Aymara language|Aymara]]:\n |data2={{lang|ay|Piruw Suyu}}\n}}\n}}\n| image_flag                = Flag of Peru.svg\n| image_coat                = Escudo_nacional_del_Per\u00fa.svg\n| other_symbol                = <div style=\"padding:0.3em;\">[[File:Gran Sello de la Rep\u00fablica del Per\u00fa.svg|100px|link=Great Seal of the State]]</div>{{native phrase|es|[[Coat of arms of Peru#Variants|Gran Sello del Estado]]|nolink=on}}<br />Great Seal of the State\n| other_symbol_type                = [[Seal (device)|National seal]]\n| national_motto                = <br />{{native name|es|\"[[Firme y feliz por la uni\u00f3n]]\"|nolink=on}}<br />\"Firm and Happy for the Union\"\n| national_anthem                = <br />{{native name|